0" stroke-width="2" data-reactid="243"><path d="M20.4997045,9.1706201 C21.4801158,8.1903106 22,6.86489899 22,5.37571157 C22,3.9415837 21.4377553,2.59810513 20.4193068,1.5801398 C19.4007673,0.56208345 18.0563988,0 16.6212625,0 C15.1861261,0 13.8417576,0.56208345 12.8232181,1.5801398 L11,3.40249296 L9.1767819,1.5801398 C8.1582424,0.56208345 6.81387391,0 5.37873754,0 C3.94360117,0 2.59923268,0.56208345 1.58069315,1.5801398 C0.56224468,2.59810513 0,3.9415837 0,5.37571157 C0,6.80983945 0.56224468,8.153318 1.57930226,9.1698958 L11.0398671,18.5888901 L20.4997045,9.1706201 Z" id="Shape" data-reactid="244"></path></g></g></svg></div><span class="LikeButton__buttonText" data-reactid="245">Like</span></button></div><div class="ListRecUnit__description" data-reactid="246"><p data-reactid="247">The director Terry Gilliam crafted one of his most distinctive and idiosyncratic pictures (no small statement) with this 1985 vision of a dystopian future, in which bureaucracy and red tape rule the day — and ruin the life of Sam Lowry (Jonathan Pryce), a mild-mannered desk clerk who inadvertently becomes an enemy of the state. Gilliam’s influences are voluminous (Franz Kafka, Jacques Tati, Orson Welles, George Orwell, German Expressionist cinema), yet he somehow synthesizes them into a style and approach that’s all his own. Look out for uproarious supporting turns by Katherine Helmond, Gilliam’s Monty Python partner Michael Palin and (in one of his first comic performances) Robert De Niro. (Palin also shines in “<b>A Fish Called Wanda</b>,” from another Monty Python alum, John Cleese.)</p></div><div class="WhereToWatchInline__whereToWatchSimple ListRecUnit__whereToWatch" data-reactid="248"><div class="WhereToWatchInline__rundownLoading" data-reactid="249"><span data-reactid="250"></span><span style="font-size:0;" data-reactid="251"></span></div></div><hr class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationHorizontalRule" data-reactid="252"/></div></div><div class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationItem" data-reactid="253"><div class="full-bleed-image-mobile" data-reactid="254"><a class="ListRecUnit__postImageLink" href="https://www.nytimes.com/watching/recommendations/watching-film-some-like-it-hot" data-reactid="255"><div data-reactid="256"><div class="CreditedMedia__watchedBadgeCreditedMediaContainer" data-reactid="257"><!-- react-empty: 258 --><picture data-reactid="259"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2018/12/04/arts/best-amazon-somelikeithot/best-amazon-somelikeithot-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" class="CreditedMedia__img" data-reactid="260"/></picture></div><div class="CreditedMedia__creditAndCaption" data-reactid="261"><span class="CreditedMedia__caption" data-reactid="262">Tony Curtis and Marilyn Monroe in “Some Like it Hot.”</span><span class="CreditedMedia__credit" data-reactid="263">United Artists</span></div></div></a></div><div class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationCopy" data-reactid="264"><p class="ListRecUnit__typeHeader" data-reactid="265">Movie</p><h2 data-reactid="266"><a class="ListRecUnit__recTitle shouldStayInPage" href="https://www.nytimes.com/watching/recommendations/watching-film-some-like-it-hot" data-reactid="267"><span class="ListRecUnit__recTitleText" data-reactid="268">‘Some Like It Hot’</span></a></h2><div class="WatchingLink__watchingLink stayInPage" data-reactid="269"><button class="SaveToWatchlistButton__saveToWatchlistButton stayInPage" data-reactid="270"><div class="_sharedIconStyles__SVGiconContainer" data-reactid="271"><svg width="15px" height="21px" viewBox="0 0 15 21" version="1.1" data-reactid="272"><title data-reactid="273">Save To Watch</title><desc data-reactid="274">Ribbon</desc><g id="RibbonIcon" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd" data-reactid="275"><g class="SaveToWatchlistButton__inactiveIcon" id="bookmark" transform="translate(1.000000, 1.000000)" stroke-width="2" stroke="#000000" data-reactid="276"><polygon id="ribbon" points="0 0 0 18.1314829 6.5 13.7981496 13 18.1314829 13 0" data-reactid="277"></polygon></g></g></svg></div><span class="SaveToWatchlistButton__buttonText" data-reactid="278">Save to Watch</span></button><button class="LikeButton__likeButton" data-reactid="279"><div class="_sharedIconStyles__SVGiconContainer" data-reactid="280"><svg width="24px" height="21px" viewBox="0 0 24 21" version="1.1" data-reactid="281"><title data-reactid="282">Like</title><desc data-reactid="283">Heart Shape</desc><g id="Like" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd" data-reactid="284"><g class="LikeButton__inactiveIcon" id="heart" transform="translate(1.000000, 1.000000)" stroke="#000000" stroke-width="2" data-reactid="285"><path d="M20.4997045,9.1706201 C21.4801158,8.1903106 22,6.86489899 22,5.37571157 C22,3.9415837 21.4377553,2.59810513 20.4193068,1.5801398 C19.4007673,0.56208345 18.0563988,0 16.6212625,0 C15.1861261,0 13.8417576,0.56208345 12.8232181,1.5801398 L11,3.40249296 L9.1767819,1.5801398 C8.1582424,0.56208345 6.81387391,0 5.37873754,0 C3.94360117,0 2.59923268,0.56208345 1.58069315,1.5801398 C0.56224468,2.59810513 0,3.9415837 0,5.37571157 C0,6.80983945 0.56224468,8.153318 1.57930226,9.1698958 L11.0398671,18.5888901 L20.4997045,9.1706201 Z" id="Shape" data-reactid="286"></path></g></g></svg></div><span class="LikeButton__buttonText" data-reactid="287">Like</span></button></div><div class="ListRecUnit__description" data-reactid="288"><p data-reactid="289">This 1959 masterpiece from Billy Wilder — voted the best comedy of all time by the BBC and the American Film Institute — features two jazz musicians (Jack Lemmon and Tony Curtis) who disguise themselves in drag to escape some gangsters. Comedy ensues when one of them falls for a seductive singer (Marilyn Monroe, in one of her best performances), while the other becomes the object of a millionaire’s desire. The screenplay, written by Wilder and I.A.L. Diamond, is both uproariously funny and tight as a drum; like the best farces, it works through every complication and every combination, landing not only on a picture-perfect conclusion but also on one of the best closing lines in all of cinema. (Wilder and Lemmon re-teamed the next year for the marvelous “<b>The Apartment</b>,” also on Prime.)</p></div><div class="WhereToWatchInline__whereToWatchSimple ListRecUnit__whereToWatch" data-reactid="290"><div class="WhereToWatchInline__rundownLoading" data-reactid="291"><span data-reactid="292"></span><span style="font-size:0;" data-reactid="293"></span></div></div><hr class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationHorizontalRule" data-reactid="294"/></div></div><div class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationItem" data-reactid="295"><div class="full-bleed-image-mobile" data-reactid="296"><a class="ListRecUnit__postImageLink" href="https://www.nytimes.com/watching/titles/the-long-strange-trip" data-reactid="297"><div data-reactid="298"><div class="CreditedMedia__watchedBadgeCreditedMediaContainer" data-reactid="299"><!-- react-empty: 300 --><picture data-reactid="301"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/25/arts/long-strange-trip-watching/25DEAD2-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" class="CreditedMedia__img" data-reactid="302"/></picture></div><div class="CreditedMedia__creditAndCaption" data-reactid="303"><span class="CreditedMedia__caption" data-reactid="304">From left, Phil Lesh, Bill Kreutzmann and Jerry Garcia of the Grateful Dead, performing in 1968 in San Francisco in the documentary “Long Strange Trip.”</span><span class="CreditedMedia__credit" data-reactid="305">Jim Marshall/The Grateful Dead, via Amazon Prime Video</span></div></div></a></div><div class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationCopy" data-reactid="306"><p class="ListRecUnit__typeHeader" data-reactid="307">Movie</p><h2 data-reactid="308"><a class="ListRecUnit__recTitle shouldStayInPage" href="https://www.nytimes.com/watching/titles/the-long-strange-trip" data-reactid="309"><span class="ListRecUnit__recTitleText" data-reactid="310">‘Long Strange Trip’</span></a></h2><div class="WatchingLink__watchingLink stayInPage" data-reactid="311"><button class="SaveToWatchlistButton__saveToWatchlistButton stayInPage" data-reactid="312"><div class="_sharedIconStyles__SVGiconContainer" data-reactid="313"><svg width="15px" height="21px" viewBox="0 0 15 21" version="1.1" data-reactid="314"><title data-reactid="315">Save To Watch</title><desc data-reactid="316">Ribbon</desc><g id="RibbonIcon" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd" data-reactid="317"><g class="SaveToWatchlistButton__inactiveIcon" id="bookmark" transform="translate(1.000000, 1.000000)" stroke-width="2" stroke="#000000" data-reactid="318"><polygon id="ribbon" points="0 0 0 18.1314829 6.5 13.7981496 13 18.1314829 13 0" data-reactid="319"></polygon></g></g></svg></div><span class="SaveToWatchlistButton__buttonText" data-reactid="320">Save to Watch</span></button><button class="LikeButton__likeButton" data-reactid="321"><div class="_sharedIconStyles__SVGiconContainer" data-reactid="322"><svg width="24px" height="21px" viewBox="0 0 24 21" version="1.1" data-reactid="323"><title data-reactid="324">Like</title><desc data-reactid="325">Heart Shape</desc><g id="Like" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd" data-reactid="326"><g class="LikeButton__inactiveIcon" id="heart" transform="translate(1.000000, 1.000000)" stroke="#000000" stroke-width="2" data-reactid="327"><path d="M20.4997045,9.1706201 C21.4801158,8.1903106 22,6.86489899 22,5.37571157 C22,3.9415837 21.4377553,2.59810513 20.4193068,1.5801398 C19.4007673,0.56208345 18.0563988,0 16.6212625,0 C15.1861261,0 13.8417576,0.56208345 12.8232181,1.5801398 L11,3.40249296 L9.1767819,1.5801398 C8.1582424,0.56208345 6.81387391,0 5.37873754,0 C3.94360117,0 2.59923268,0.56208345 1.58069315,1.5801398 C0.56224468,2.59810513 0,3.9415837 0,5.37571157 C0,6.80983945 0.56224468,8.153318 1.57930226,9.1698958 L11.0398671,18.5888901 L20.4997045,9.1706201 Z" id="Shape" data-reactid="328"></path></g></g></svg></div><span class="LikeButton__buttonText" data-reactid="329">Like</span></button></div><div class="ListRecUnit__description" data-reactid="330"><p data-reactid="331">The three-decade journey of the psychedelic rock band the Grateful Dead is brought to vivid life in this six-part, four-hour documentary from director Amir Bar-Lev (“The Tillman Story”). And Bar-Lev takes full advantage of the expansive run time, digging in to the band’s roots, formation, stumbles, successes and even the hierarchies of the superfan Deadheads. The treasure trove of previously unseen archival materials and rare recordings will no doubt please that coterie. But the film has even more to offer to casual admirers and even newcomers, who will come away with a better understanding of what made this band (and the misfits they attracted) so special. (Music-minded documentary fans will also want to check out the peerless concert docs “<b>Stop Making Sense</b>”<b> </b>and “<b>The Last Waltz</b>.”)</p></div><div class="WhereToWatchInline__whereToWatchSimple ListRecUnit__whereToWatch" data-reactid="332"><div class="WhereToWatchInline__rundownLoading" data-reactid="333"><span data-reactid="334"></span><span style="font-size:0;" data-reactid="335"></span></div></div><hr class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationHorizontalRule" data-reactid="336"/></div></div><div class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationItem" data-reactid="337"><div class="full-bleed-image-mobile" data-reactid="338"><a class="ListRecUnit__postImageLink" href="https://www.nytimes.com/watching/titles/desperately-seeking-susan" data-reactid="339"><div data-reactid="340"><div class="CreditedMedia__watchedBadgeCreditedMediaContainer" data-reactid="341"><!-- react-empty: 342 --><picture data-reactid="343"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2018/03/08/watching/desperately-seeking-susan-watching/nightcrawler-watching-slide-BPWA-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" class="CreditedMedia__img" data-reactid="344"/></picture></div><div class="CreditedMedia__