 in a flat, pseudo-documentary, newsreel aesthetic that rendered the horrifying images of walking dead flesh-eaters seem terrifyingly real. In the half-century since its release, it’s been justifiably praised for its social commentary and political subtext (particularly with regards to its African-American lead, and the unexpected payoff of its grim final scene). But it also remains, after all these years, scary as hell. (If you’re looking for a newer chiller, try out “<b>Hereditary</b>.”)</p></div><div class="WhereToWatchInline__whereToWatchSimple ListRecUnit__whereToWatch" data-reactid="1052"><div class="WhereToWatchInline__rundownLoading" data-reactid="1053"><span data-reactid="1054"></span><span style="font-size:0;" data-reactid="1055"></span></div></div><hr class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationHorizontalRule" data-reactid="1056"/></div></div><div class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationItem" data-reactid="1057"><div class="full-bleed-image-mobile" data-reactid="1058"><a class="ListRecUnit__postImageLink" href="https://www.nytimes.com/watching/titles/untouchables-watching" data-reactid="1059"><div data-reactid="1060"><div class="CreditedMedia__watchedBadgeCreditedMediaContainer" data-reactid="1061"><!-- react-empty: 1062 --><picture data-reactid="1063"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2019/01/25/arts/25UNTOUCHABLES/25UNTOUCHABLES-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" class="CreditedMedia__img" data-reactid="1064"/></picture></div><div class="CreditedMedia__creditAndCaption" data-reactid="1065"><span class="CreditedMedia__caption" data-reactid="1066">From left, Andy Garcia, Sean Connery, Kevin Costner and Charles Martin Smith in “The Untouchables."</span><span class="CreditedMedia__credit" data-reactid="1067">Paramount Pictures</span></div></div></a></div><div class="ListRecUnit__listRecommendationCopy" data-reactid="1068"><p class="ListRecUnit__typeHeader" data-reactid="1069">Movie</p><h2 data-reactid="1070"><a class="ListRecUnit__recTitle shouldStayInPage" h