 his finest performances, as J.J. Gittes, a laid-back Los Angeles gumshoe who gets in way over his head. Faye Dunaway takes the conventions of the slinky femme fatale and turns them into a portrait of genuine pain and abuse. And John Huston (who directed “The Maltese Falcon<i>,”</i> an essential private eye movie of the ’40s) is chillingly effective as a true symbol of unapologetic evil. (The stark, disturbing Dunaway vehicle “<b>Eyes of Laura Mars</b>” is also currently streaming on Prime, as is another terrific ‘70s action flick, “<b>The Taking of Pelham 123</b>.”)","imageCrops":{"thumbnail":{"height":252,"width":252,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/19/watching/chinatown-watching-recommendation/chinatown-watching-recommendation-smallSquare252-v4.jpg"},"largeImage":{"height":899,"width":1600,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/19/watching/chinatown-watching-recommendation/chinatown-watching-recommendation-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600-v4.jpg"},"smallImage":{"height":293,"width":440,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/19/watching/chinatown-watching-recommendation/chinatown-watching-recommendation-mediumThreeByTwo440-v4.jpg"},"facebook":{"height":549,"width":1050,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/19/watching/chinatown-watching-recommendation/chinatown-watching-recommendation-facebookJumbo-v4.jpg"},"recCard":{"height":432,"width":768,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/19/watching/chinatown-watching-recommendation/chinatown-watching-recommendation-videoSixteenByNine768-v4.jpg"},"recCardSmallScreens":{"height":322,"width":573,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/19/watching/chinatown-watching-recommendation/chinatown-watching-recommendation-largeWidescreen573-v5.jpg"},"largeHorizontal":{"height":682,"width":1024,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/19/watching/chinatown-watching-recommendation/chinatown-watching-recommendation-largeHorizontalJumbo-v4.jpg"},"master":{"height":431,"width":768,"