ilence’","description":"Martin Scorsese is best known for kinetic gangster movies like “Goodfellas,” “The Departed,” and “Casino,” but sometimes another Scorsese surfaces, the director of quiet, austere meditations on religious faith like “The Last Temptation of Christ,” “Kundun” and this 2016 adaptation of the novel by Shusaku Endo. Following two 17th-century Jesuit priests (played with modesty and restraint by Adam Garfield and Adam Driver) as they attempt an ill-fated missionary journey into Japan, it explicitly tackles one of the most fundamental questions of religion: How can we pray without assurance that our prayers are being heard? Scorsese sheds his customary stylistic flourishes and explores the central theological problem with humble solemnity. It’s one of his riskiest films, and one of his most rewarding. (Scorsese’s <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/watching/recommendations/watching-film-hugo\"><b>Hugo</b></a>” is also on Prime.)","imageCrops":{"thumbnail":{"height":252,"width":252,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/04/17/arts/silence-watching-recommendation/silence-watching-recommendation-smallSquare252-v2.jpg"},"largeImage":{"height":900,"width":1600,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/04/17/arts/silence-watching-recommendation/17watching-recommendation-slide-KSQT-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg"},"smallImage":{"height":293,"width":440,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/04/17/arts/silence-watching-recommendation/silence-watching-recommendation-mediumThreeByTwo440-v2.jpg"},"facebook":{"height":550,"width":1050,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/04/17/arts/silence-watching-recommendation/17watching-recommendation-slide-KSQT-facebookJumbo.jpg"},"recCard":{"height":432,"width":768,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/04/17/arts/silence-watching-recommendation/17watching-recommendation-slide-KSQT-videoSixteenByNine768.jpg"},"recCardSmallScreens":{"height":322,"width":573,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/