director David Cronenberg rarely made traditional horror films, and this 1983 adaptation of the best-seller by Stephen King is no exception. In lieu of his customary surrealism and body horror, however, Cronenberg burrows into the psychological intensity of King’s tale. It’s as much science-fiction as horror, focusing on a regular Joe (Christopher Walken, muted and effective) who comes out of a five-year coma with the ability to see the futures of those he touches. This thoughtful and tricky picture is as interested in moral dilemmas and historical ramifications as it is in thrills and chills: It’s like a particularly potent “Twilight Zone” episode, equal parts taut and thought-provoking.","imageCrops":{"thumbnail":{"height":252,"width":252,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/10/04/watching/deadzone-watching-recommendation/deadzone-watching-recommendation-smallSquare252-v8.jpg"},"largeImage":{"height":580,"width":1032,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/10/04/watching/deadzone-watching-recommendation/deadzone-watching-recommendation-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600-v8.jpg"},"smallImage":{"height":293,"width":440,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/10/04/watching/deadzone-watching-recommendation/deadzone-watching-recommendation-mediumThreeByTwo440-v7.jpg"},"facebook":{"height":545,"width":1042,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/10/04/watching/deadzone-watching-recommendation/deadzone-watching-recommendation-facebookJumbo-v9.jpg"},"recCard":{"height":432,"width":768,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/10/04/watching/deadzone-watching-recommendation/deadzone-watching-recommendation-videoSixteenByNine768-v7.jpg"},"recCardSmallScreens":{"height":322,"width":573,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/10/04/watching/deadzone-watching-recommendation/deadzone-watching-recommendation-largeWidescreen573-v7.jpg"},"largeHorizontal":{"height":580,"width":870,"url":"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/10/04/watching/deadzone-watching-recom